where we have used p∗ = r∗qθ, and Df is the f -divergence defined in equation (7). We can derive a ratio loss from (16) by extracting all the terms in rφ, leading to the minimisation of LB(rφ). The role of the discriminator in GANs is again taken by the ratio r that provides information about the relationship between the two distributions. This ratio loss, like in Uehara et al. (2016), is equivalent to the ratio loss we derived using divergence minimisation (8), since:
LB (rφ (x)) = Ep∗[−f ′(rφ(x))] + Eqθ(x)[rφ(x)f ′(rφ(x)) − f (rφ(x))] (17)
= Ep∗[−f ′(rφ(x))] + Eqθ(x)[f †(f ′(rφ(x)))]. (18)
The equivalence of the second terms in (17) and (18) can be derived by using the definition of the dual function:
f †(f ′(x)) = mrax rf ′(x) − f (r). (19)


