The maximum is attained at x = r, leading to the identity
f †(f ′(rφ(x))) = rφ(x)f ′(rφ(x)) − f (rφ(x)). (20)
If we follow the strategy we used in previous sections to obtain a generative loss, by collecting the terms in equation (16) dependent on qθ, we obtain:
L(qθ) =Eqθ(x)[rφ(x)f ′(rφ(x))] − Eqθ(x)[f (rφ(x))] + Df [p∗(x)||qθ(x)]. (21)
But this does not lead to a useful generative loss since there are terms involving qθ whose density is always unknown, similar to the difficulty we encountered with divergence minimisation in equation (12). Since we can use any generative loss that drives the ratio to one, we can employ other losses, like the alternatives described in section 2.2 . One approximation suggested by Uehara et al. (2016) is to assume p∗ ≈ rφqθ, i.e. assume a near-optimal ratio, which reduces the f -divergence to:
